observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
appoint or designate a GSO who shall specifically take custody and be accountable for all the properties of the Municipality;

require the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of the physical count of PPE of the Municipality and undertake all other procedures prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
instruct the GSO-designate and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records after the physical count and effect the necessary adjustments, if any;


require the GSO-designate to submit to the Auditor the complete RPCPPE as of December 31 not later than January 31 of the ensuing year, and


instruct the GSO-designate to undertake proper disposal of unserviceable properties, if any.

To correct the aforementioned deficiencies, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
instruct all the heads of offices to fill out all the data in the PR and indicate the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items being requested to be purchased and avoid indicating the brand name except for replacement of parts; 


instruct the GSO Designate to see to it that all the data in the RFQ/Canvass Paper are completely filled out and that the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items being canvassed are indicated therein except the brand name unless the items are replacements of parts;
instruct the GSO Designate to require the bidders to indicate in the RFQ/Bill of Quantities the brand name of items they are quoting which shall be incorporated in the PO;
instruct the GSO Designate to see to it that all data in the PO are completely filled out and the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items being ordered are indicated therein including the brand name of the items as indicated by the winning bidder in the RFQ/Canvass Paper/Bill of Quantities;
instruct the   Agency Inspector and the GSO Designate   who sign the inspection and acceptance portions of the AIR respectively that such document is properly filled out and the exact unit of measure and complete specifications of items accepted and inspected including the brand name of the items be indicated therein;
require the Municipal Accountant and the head of office in charge for the distribution of goods with aggregate cost of Ᵽ48,862,998.00 to submit the Distribution Lists, otherwise, these transactions shall be suspended in audit;
require the head of office in charge in the distribution of goods for the under-distribution with equivalent amount of ₱230,401.00 and over-distribution of Ᵽ76,640.00 to submit an explanation for these deficiencies;
instruct the Municipal Accountant and the head of office in charge in the distribution of goods that henceforth, see to it that such are supported with Pre-Master List of Beneficiaries, pictures of the goods to be distributed, duly accomplished Distribution Lists indicating among others the title and date of activity, the name and address of recipients, the quantity and complete specifications of items distributed, signature of recipients and certification of the head of office that the Distribution Lists are true and correct and pictures during distribution;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer to submit the original copy official receipts of remittances to GSIS in the total amount of ₱5,191,651.15 and henceforth, attach said document to the disbursement voucher;


require the GSO Designate to submit PAR for the issuances of non-expendable properties aggregating ₱4,946,564.00;

require the GSO Designate to submit ICS for issuances of semi-expendable properties aggregating ₱162,579.00;


l. require the Municipal Accountant to issue a certification that the previous cash advance of the payee has been liquidated before processing payment for another cash advance;  
m. require the Municipal Accountant to see to it that cash advances for payroll are supported with payroll duly signed by the signatories indicated in Boxes A to D therein without the signatures of the payees, as basis of the amount to be cash advanced; 
 require the head of office in charge of the activity for which meals and/or snacks shall be served to participants or visitors to see to it that these are supported with duly accomplished Attendance Sheet indicating the date and title of the activity, the name and signatures of participants, pictures taken during the activity and pictures showing that the participants are taking their meals/snacks; 
require the GSO Designate to see to it that Delivery Receipts are dated and the Municipal Treasurer to make sure that the Sales Invoices and Official/Collection Receipts are dated before releasing payments to suppliers/contractors, and
require the Municipal Accountant to see to it that disbursements are supported with complete documentation.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:
4.13.1		the Municipal Budget Officer to be guided by the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs as required in pertinent provisions of Local Budget Circular No. 112 dated June 10, 2016, in the preparation of annual and supplemental budgets to ensure uniform and correct classification of accounts;
4.13.2 the Municipal Accountant to also be guided by the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs by considering the purpose of the expenditure in the recording of transactions in the books of accounts, in order to reflect the correct nature of expenditures and to achieve the delivery of accurate information as a basis for sound decision-making by the users of the financial statements;
4.13.3 the Municipal Accountant to submit immediately the aforementioned lacking documents to the Office of the Auditor, otherwise, a Notice of Suspension will be issued; and
4.13.4 the Municipal Accountant to observe strict compliance with Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 and pertinent provisions of COA Circular 2012-001 to ascertain the validity, propriety and legality of transactions.

We also recommended that Management be guided by the provisions of Department of Budget and Management (DBM) Budget Circular No. 2024-2, dated August 2, 2024, on the Guidelines on the Payment of Communication Expenses of Certain Government Personnel, upon termination of their existing contracts with the telecommunications provider.

In order to present the correct balances of Inventories and PPE accounts in the financial statements, we reiterated our previous recommendations that the Municipal Mayor:
7.8.1 require the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of the physical count of all Inventories and PPE of the Municipality and avail of the procedures of One-Time Cleansing of PPE balances prescribed under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
7.8.2 instruct the GSO Designate and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records after the physical count and effect the necessary adjustments, if any;
7.8.3 require the GSO Designate to submit to the Auditor the semestral RPCI not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
7.8.4 require the GSO Designate to submit to the Auditor the RPCPPE as of December 31 not later than January 31 of the ensuing year, and
7.8.5 instruct the GSO Designate to undertake proper disposal of unserviceable properties, if any.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to:
11.6.1	stop the practice of splitting contracts just to avoid public bidding;
11.6.2 	conduct competitive public bidding for all procurements and resort to alternative methods of procurement only when the conditions provided in the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, now IRR of RA No. 12009, are met in order to obtain the most advantageous price for the government.

We recommended that the LCE:

instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical count of all PPEs as required under Section 156 of COA Circular No. 92-386 and Section 124 of MNGAS for LGUs to ascertain, as well as to provide basis on the validity, existence, serviceability and correctness of the properties presented in the financial statement;

require the Inventory Committee to prepare the RCPPE instead of the Municipal Accountant as they were the ones who conducted the validation of PPEs, hence ascertaining the reliability of the report;

instruct the Municipal Accountant and Inventory Committee to reclassify the properties costing ₱15,000.00 and below to semi-expendable properties; and

instruct the Property Officer, the Head of Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to adhere with the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA Circular 2020-06 dated January 31, 2020 for the conduct of physical count of properties; recognition of PPE items found at station; disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items; and for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, in order to reflect more reliable and accurate balances of PPE accounts, hence to convey precise information useful in decision making and accountability for these properties.

